Investigate this failing pipeline caused by a dependency version bump and produce a fix plan.

<pipeline>
  <pipeline_url>{{pipeline_url}}</pipeline_url>
</pipeline>

Follow this two-phase procedure:

<investigation_phase>
  <step>Use `get_pipeline_failing_jobs` to retrieve failing jobs for the pipeline.
  Capture each failing job's **name, ID, and web URL** — these are required for the
  per-job link in the final comment (do NOT substitute the pipeline URL).</step>
  <step>Use `get_job_logs` to retrieve logs for each failing job. Capture error
  messages, stack traces, and **failing test names with their source `file:line`
  locations** (e.g. `test_models.py:226` — the line is in the pytest/jest/rspec
  output near the failure). If the job runs a test framework (pytest, jest, rspec,
  mocha, go test, cargo test, etc.), locate its final summary line that reports
  counts — e.g. pytest's `1 failed, 12 passed, 11 warnings in 0.10s` — and capture
  those numbers verbatim into the `<pipeline_errors>` section.</step>
  <step>Use `get_merge_request` to identify the merge request associated with this pipeline.</step>
  <step>Use `list_merge_request_diffs` to see what files changed in the dependency bump MR.</step>
  <step>Use `find_files` to locate dependency manifest files (requirements.txt, setup.py, setup.cfg,
  pyproject.toml, Gemfile, package.json, go.mod, pom.xml, etc.), then `read_file` on them
  to extract the dependency name, ecosystem, and old/new versions.</step>
  <step>If vulnerability IDs are mentioned in the logs, use `list_vulnerabilities` and `get_vulnerability_details` to gather CVE context.</step>
</investigation_phase>

<analysis_phase>
  <step>Use `grep` to find all imports of the bumped dependency. Use `find_files` to locate any other files that reference it, **including test files** (a common miss).</step>
  <step>Use `read_file` on each match to understand the usage pattern.</step>
  <step>Cross-reference the pipeline errors with the code locations and the changelog information gathered in the investigation phase.</step>
  <step>For each breaking change, categorize it (API removed, function signature changed, import path moved, new required parameter, type change, behavior change) and produce a concrete fix step with old code → new code.</step>
</analysis_phase>

Present your findings and fix plan in this structured format:
<output_format>
  <dependency>
    <name>Package name</name>
    <ecosystem>python/ruby/node/go/java</ecosystem>
    <old_version>Version before bump</old_version>
    <new_version>Version after bump</new_version>
  </dependency>
  <merge_request>
    <url>The merge request URL associated with this pipeline</url>
  </merge_request>
  <pipeline_errors>
    List of error messages, stack traces, failing test names, and the final test-runner
    summary line verbatim (e.g. `1 failed, 12 passed, 11 warnings in 0.10s`) if present.
  </pipeline_errors>
  <changed_files>
    Files modified in the MR
  </changed_files>
  <external_dependency_info>
    Changelog entries, breaking changes, deprecation notices, and release notes URL from
    the package registry. Leave empty if no registry-fetch tool is available — do not
    reconstruct from training memory.
  </external_dependency_info>
  <vulnerability_info>
    CVE details if applicable
  </vulnerability_info>
  <root_cause>High-level description of what broke and why</root_cause>
  <breaking_changes>
    For each breaking change:
    <breaking_change>
      <category>API removed / function signature changed / import path moved / new required parameter / type change / behavior change</category>
      <description>What specifically changed</description>
      <affected_files>List of files and line numbers affected</affected_files>
    </breaking_change>
  </breaking_changes>
  <fix_plan>
    For each fix:
    <step>
      <file>Path to the file to modify</file>
      <action>edit / create / delete / run_command</action>
      <description>What to change and why</description>
      <details>Specific old code -> new code, or command to run</details>
    </step>
  </fix_plan>
  <confidence>high / medium / low</confidence>
</output_format>
